One of the most memorable moments of my life was when I was at a relative's house near the sea coast, in the middle of summer, and one night there was a horrifying storm, wind and thunder so strong I could not even sleep, the actual full fury of nature. People died! In the ...

morning, I found out that a nearby river HAD ALTERED ITS PATH, it went around the beach, but somehow due to the rainwater entering into it, it overflowed and changed its trajectory to pierce it, an actual geographical change, a brutal metamorphosis of the physical terrain.

I walked around the small seaside town and nothing was the same, people seemed confused on a subconscious level. Looking at the overturned and semi-sunk boats, the overflowing waters, the ruined beach, the new river trajectory, all of this new, my eyes one of the first to see it

This is a feeling very few men get to experience, the realization that a radical geological change has taken place in front of your eyes. Everything felt somehow dreamlike, unusual. There is no name for this feeling, only thing I can compare it to was the "newness" experienced...

... by Mary after seeing the post-Resurrection Christ, it's truly something that is hard to express with words. I will carry the memory with me forever, and let it ferment in, and nurture, my mind. An actual change on all layers. Felt like sharing this w/ my friends here (you)

We had one chicken at my village, that was the sole survivor of a fox attack on the coop (one of the walls had a small hole hidden behind some crates). It lived, and after we got a new batch of chickens, the cockerel almost raped it to death. Had to put it away from the rest...

... in the wood storage building, where it spent a winter in complete darkness, otherwise it could not have survived. The cockerel was slaughtered, and then the chicken was taken back to the coop. It survived for like 7 years, a shitton for a hen. Absolute beast of a chicken...
More of just a story to show how brutal nature is sometimes, and how we can still survive even the hardest of times
